<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>WRITTEN EVIDENCE SUBMITTED BY</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Hampshire and Isle of Wight Wildlife Trust on behalf of The New Forest Non-Native Plants Project,</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We note that the Inquiry will examine ‘the case for any change in the law regarding invasive species’ and ‘any lessons for England and Wales from the experience of Scotland’s invasive species legislation and controls’.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We ask the Environmental Audit Committee to consider the Law Commission’s review of Wildlife Law, in particular the Law Commission’s Provisional Proposal 8-7 ‘that the power to make species control orders on the same model as under the Wildlife and Natural Environment (Scotland) Act 2011 should be adopted by our new legal regime’. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We ask the Environmental Audit Committee to consider the introduction of species control orders ‘made by statutory notice if the relevant body is unable to ascertain the name and address of any owner of occupier’, referred to in paragraph 8.76 of the Law Commission’s consultation paper on the reform of Wildlife Law.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We consider that the introduction of species control orders, in particular in situations where the name and address of the owners can not be ascertained, would be of significant benefit to the control and eradication of invasive non-native species.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Brief introduction and reason for submitting evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This submission has been prepared by Hampshire and Isle of Wight Wildlife </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Trust on behalf of The New Forest Non-Native Plants Project. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Hampshire and Isle of Wight Wildlife Trust is a registered charity (number </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">201081) and a Company limited by guarantee and registered in England </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(number 676313). </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The New Forest Non-Native Plants Project commenced in 2009 to stop the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">spread of invasive non-native plants in the New Forest area, particularly along </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rivers and in wetland habitats. It is hosted by Hampshire and Isle of Wight </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wildlife Trust and is supported by a partnership of organisations including the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Forestry Commission, Environment Agency, Natural England and the New </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Forest National Park Authority. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Hampshire and Isle of Wight Wildlife Trust welcomes the opportunity to submit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">written evidence to the Inquiry. The New Forest Non-Native Plants Project </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">contributes to the implementation of The Invasive Non-Native Species </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Framework </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Strategy for Great Britain (DEFRA, 2008) through a) control and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eradication of invasive non-native plants, b) building awareness and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">understanding of the problems caused by invasive non-native species and c) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">commissioning research into the impact of invasive non-native plants and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">novel methods of control. As recognised by the Framework Strategy, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">successful implementation relies on a ‘strong partnership approach’ with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">landowners; the New Forest Non-Native Plants Project has established strong </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">links with landowners but progress towards eradication of invasive non-native </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">plants at the catchment scale is being hampered by the inability to ascertain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the ownership of certain areas of land. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Hampshire and Isle of Wight Wildlife Trust wishes to draw the Inquiry’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">attention to the Law Commission’s review of Wildlife Law, in particular the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">proposal to introduce powers to make species control orders. We consider </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that the introduction of species control orders, in particular in situations where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the name and address of the land owner can not be ascertained, would be of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">significant benefit to the control and eradication of invasive non-native </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">species.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Evidence submitted by Hampshire and Isle of Wight Wildlife Trust</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We note that the Inquiry will examine ‘the case for any change in the law </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">regarding invasive species’ and ‘any lessons for England and Wales from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">experience of Scotland’s invasive species legislation and controls’. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Hampshire and Isle of Wight Wildlife Trust considers that changes in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">legislation are required to enable invasive non-native species to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">successfully controlled and eradicated at the catchment scale. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is an offence under Section 14(2) of the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘plant or otherwise cause to grow in the wild’ any plant listed in Part II of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Schedule 9 of this Act. Although Hampshire and Isle of Wight Wildlife Trust </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recognises that responsibility therefore rests with riparian landowners to stop </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the spread of plants listed in Schedule 9, we consider that landowners need </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">advice, encouragement and practical help to enable invasive non-native plants </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to be successfully eradicated at the catchment scale.  The New Forest Non-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Native Plants Project was therefore set up to liaise with landowners and offer </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">advice and practical help to control relevant invasive non-native species along </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">river valleys and in wetland habitats in the New Forest area.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Since the start of The New Forest Non-Native Plants Project in 2009, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Project Officer has identified riparian owners along relevant watercourses to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">offer advice and help with the control of invasive non-native species, for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">example giant hogweed and Himalayan balsam. The vast majority of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">landowners have co-operated with the Project Officer, recognised the need </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for the control of invasive non-native species on their land and have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">understood the importance of a ‘joined-up’ approach with neighbouring </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">landowners to tackle the spread of invasive non-native plants at the catchment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">scale. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, in a minority of cases, the Project Officer has been unable to identify </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the owner(s) of the land, despite extensive research. The inability to identify </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the current landowner of even a single parcel of land presents a challenge to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">successful eradication at the catchment scale, as seed from plants growing on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">this land can fall into the adjacent watercourse and be carried downstream to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re-infest areas where landowners, contractors and volunteers have worked </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hard to control the invasive species. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">During 2012 the Law Commission undertook a consultation exercise in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">relation to its review of wildlife law. Chapter 8 of the consultation document </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(Law Commission Consultation Paper No 206) considered the control of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">invasive non-native species and included Provisional Proposal 8-7 for ‘the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">power to make species control orders on the same model as under the Wildlife </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and Natural Environment (Scotland) Act 2011’.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Hampshire and Isle of Wight Wildlife Trust fully supported this Provisional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Proposal in our response to the Law Commission dated 8 November 2012. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We welcomed the proposal for species control orders to require a person to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">destroy invasive non-native species on their property. We welcomed the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">introduction of species control orders which can permit a person to enter land </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">without the need for permission from the owner or occupier (normally with 14 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">days notice) to carry out operations required by the order. We welcomed the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">proposal for emergency species control orders which would permit a person to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">enter land to undertake work without the need to give the owner or occupier </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">14 days notice. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In our response to the Law Commission’s consultation, we pointed out that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">one of the major problems currently facing the New Forest Non-Native Plants </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Project is how to deal with invasive non-native species on land where the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">owner can not be traced. We cited the example of the Cadnam River where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we are helping landowners to eradicate the Schedule 9 plant called Himalayan </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">balsam but where the owner of one parcel of land can not be identified, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">despite extensive research involving </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">inter alia</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Land Registry searches, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">interviews with neighbouring landowners, correspondence with the son of a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">previous owner, correspondence with the Highways Agency who once owned </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the land and discussions with local residents. We have therefore been unable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to tackle the Himalayan balsam on this parcel of land and are acutely </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">conscious that all the effort/time/resources being expended further </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">downstream is being jeopardised by the seeds being shed from plants growing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on this particular parcel of land. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.9 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We were therefore very encouraged to note that (in paragraph 8.76 of the Law </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Commission Consultation Paper No 206) ‘a species control order can be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">made by statutory notice if the relevant body is unable to ascertain the name </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and address of any owner or occupier’. We would strongly welcome the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">introduction of species control orders which can be imposed on land where the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ownership can not be ascertained. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations for action</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Following the Law Commission’s consultation exercise during 2012 (Law </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Commission Consultation Paper No 206), a Wildlife Law Interim Statement (15 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">October 2013) has been published which sets out the Law Commission’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">conclusions in advance of it drafting legislation. The Interim Statement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recommends (paragraph 1.83) the introduction of species control orders in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">England and Wales. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">/Con</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Hampshire and Isle of Wight Wildlife Trust asks the Environmental Audit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Committee to consider endorsing the Law Commission’s recommendation for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the introduction of species control orders in England and Wales. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">introduction of species control orders would allow entry onto land in order to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">control an invasive non-native species and would be of particular benefit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">where the relevant body is unable to ascertain the name and address of any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">owner or occupier.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We consider the introduction of species control orders would significantly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">contribute to the successful control and eradication of invasive non-native </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">plants at the catchment scale, thereby furthering the implementation of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Invasive Non-Native </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Species Framework Strategy for Great Britain.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">7 January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>